WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.840
So yeah, while Matt and Rowan are setting up here

00:00:03.840 --> 00:00:07.840
, I just want to introduce them.

00:00:07.840 --> 00:00:09.990
Because it's not every day that you get to see people

00:00:09.990 --> 00:00:12.640
visiting from the future, but you're about to see that

00:00:12.640 --> 00:00:14.180
happen right now.

00:00:14.180 --> 00:00:16.920
We're very fortunate to be visited by some researchers who are

00:00:16.920 --> 00:00:20.270
coming to tell us about the future of science publishing and communication

00:00:20.270 --> 00:00:21.130
from the future.

00:00:21.160 --> 00:00:23.500
It's a special day today.

00:00:23.500 --> 00:00:26.170
Rowan is the CEO and founder of Curvenote,

00:00:26.170 --> 00:00:32.830
where he leads the development of tools designed to free scientific communication

00:00:32.940 --> 00:00:34.280
from PDFs.

00:00:34.280 --> 00:00:37.390
Rowan is also the founder of the Continuous Science Foundation

00:00:37.480 --> 00:00:40.420
, a non-profit organization for the next generation of science

00:00:40.420 --> 00:00:41.240
communication.

00:00:41.240 --> 00:00:45.020
CSF is developing standards to support a more continuous and compos

00:00:45.030 --> 00:00:46.520
able model of science.

00:00:46.520 --> 00:00:48.380
Rowan is also visiting his alma mater today.

00:00:48.380 --> 00:00:50.640
He has a PhD from UBC in geophysics,

00:00:50.640 --> 00:00:55.500
computational geophysics, and has received multiple awards for innovative

00:00:55.500 --> 00:00:59.360
research dissemination and open education resources, including visible geology,

00:00:59.360 --> 00:01:03.660
and interactive geoscience modeling application used by over 1 million

00:01:03.660 --> 00:01:03.660
students globally.

00:01:03.660 --> 00:01:08.590
Matt Akamatsu is an assistant professor of biology at the

00:01:08.590 --> 00:01:09.420
University of Washington in Seattle.

00:01:09.420 --> 00:01:11.910
He's also the co-founder of the Discourse Graph

00:01:11.910 --> 00:01:16.260
s Project, supported by the Chan Zuckerberg Initiative and Nav

00:01:16.260 --> 00:01:17.660
igation Fund.

00:01:17.660 --> 00:01:20.830
They're creating systems and software tools for modular research in the

00:01:20.830 --> 00:01:21.410
age of AI.

00:01:21.420 --> 00:01:24.850
Matt Akamatsu is a recipient of the 2020 Porter Prize

00:01:24.850 --> 00:01:29.570
for Research Excellence from the American Society of Cell Biology, the

00:01:29.610 --> 00:01:33.240
K99 Pathway to Independence Award, and the Experimental

00:01:33.240 --> 00:01:35.290
Foundations Beyond the Journal Award.

00:01:35.320 --> 00:01:38.610
Matt Akamatsu received his PhD in biophysics at

00:01:38.610 --> 00:01:42.420
Yale, did postdoc at Berkeley, and started at IS

00:01:42.420 --> 00:01:43.860
LAB in UW.

00:01:43.860 --> 00:01:44.860
Take it away, guys.

00:01:44.870 --> 00:01:46.860
Matt Akamatsu: Excellent.

00:01:46.870 --> 00:01:49.860
Thank you so much.

00:01:49.860 --> 00:01:55.380
I'm absolutely thrilled and excited to talk to you today about

00:01:55.380 --> 00:01:59.990
the movement towards modular open science and some of the work that

00:01:59.990 --> 00:02:03.250
we're doing at Continuous Science Foundation and Curb Note

00:02:03.320 --> 00:02:05.340
towards these goals.

00:02:05.340 --> 00:02:08.790
And so today, science is trapped in this sort of paper

00:02:08.900 --> 00:02:09.960
-shaped box.

00:02:09.980 --> 00:02:14.660
We're communicating our discoveries using print-era concepts that const

00:02:14.660 --> 00:02:19.110
rain the way that we communicate, evaluate, and ultimately build

00:02:19.110 --> 00:02:22.340
towards scientific knowledge and progress.

00:02:22.340 --> 00:02:26.860
But the science that's being produced has changed so massively with

00:02:26.900 --> 00:02:32.560
larger data sets, larger scale collaborations, continuous sharing of computational

00:02:32.560 --> 00:02:34.240
notebooks and graphs.

00:02:34.240 --> 00:02:39.240
The way that we communicate science has really not kept up to

00:02:39.240 --> 00:02:40.460
that change.

00:02:40.560 --> 00:02:45.560
Our mission at the Continuous Science Foundation is to help move

00:02:45.560 --> 00:02:50.340
the open science movement from sort of the sole focus on reading

00:02:50.340 --> 00:02:54.700
and access, the open access movement, to a future that

00:02:54.700 --> 00:02:58.970
's more focused on utility and reuse that's built on these

00:02:58.980 --> 00:03:05.530
same foundations of openness and designed for modern discovery patterns, where

00:03:05.530 --> 00:03:09.620
the code, data, protocols, methods are available.

00:03:09.620 --> 00:03:10.620
They're interconnected.

00:03:10.620 --> 00:03:11.820
They're modular.

00:03:11.820 --> 00:03:16.580
They can be composed together through remixing and sort of importing

00:03:16.680 --> 00:03:18.460
somebody else's work.

00:03:18.460 --> 00:03:21.910
And that really is the ethos of science, is building

00:03:22.010 --> 00:03:25.560
upon other people's work, is standing on the shoulders of

00:03:25.870 --> 00:03:28.620
giants.

00:03:28.620 --> 00:03:32.580
There's an illusion published by Louis Albert Necker in 18

00:03:32.580 --> 00:03:33.300
32.

00:03:33.300 --> 00:03:34.880
He was a crystallographer.

00:03:34.900 --> 00:03:36.700
And this is the Necker cube.

00:03:36.700 --> 00:03:39.340
And it's 12 lines on a page.

00:03:39.340 --> 00:03:42.090
But if you stare at the bottom, the left sort of

00:03:42.090 --> 00:03:45.130
side pops out and it changes and it flips orientation.

00:03:45.180 --> 00:03:47.860
If you look at the top, again, there's this

00:03:47.860 --> 00:03:49.460
perceptual reversal.

00:03:49.500 --> 00:03:55.570
It has the same underlying data, but different interpretations, different

00:03:55.570 --> 00:03:59.340
stories that you can tell about fitting those data points together.

00:03:59.340 --> 00:04:03.210
And this is the way that I like to think about modular

00:04:03.210 --> 00:04:08.940
science, is we have these Lego bricks, these modules of

00:04:08.940 --> 00:04:11.380
science, the components, the figures, the equations, the

00:04:11.380 --> 00:04:14.280
data sets, the scripts, the visualization routines, those protocols

00:04:14.280 --> 00:04:17.110
, questions, claims, evidence, and they're in these

00:04:17.210 --> 00:04:18.700
different spaces.

00:04:18.700 --> 00:04:21.250
They can live on the floor, scattered.

00:04:21.260 --> 00:04:25.230
They can be sorted into buckets or assembled on a shelf as

00:04:25.230 --> 00:04:27.340
sort of a published paper.

00:04:27.340 --> 00:04:33.110
And so the assembly into a paper, it tells a story

00:04:33.110 --> 00:04:33.420
.

00:04:33.500 --> 00:04:36.380
It's that narrative that introduces a new concept.

00:04:36.380 --> 00:04:37.880
It changes minds.

00:04:37.900 --> 00:04:41.830
The components of scientific discourse are bundled together into that sort

00:04:41.830 --> 00:04:44.610
of narrative, that traditional way of publishing.

00:04:44.620 --> 00:04:48.620
This composed artifact, that paper, that story.

00:04:48.630 --> 00:04:56.700
But our scientific ways, our sharing industry, and the standards

00:04:56.770 --> 00:05:00.400
today, they demand that you sort of glue that trophy together

00:05:00.400 --> 00:05:01.740
when you share it.

00:05:01.740 --> 00:05:05.520
That eight page paper with its four sort of paneled figures

00:05:05.530 --> 00:05:07.260
, a zip file supplement.

00:05:07.260 --> 00:05:08.840
It's all fused together.

00:05:08.860 --> 00:05:11.970
And if you want to reuse a figure or a data set

00:05:11.970 --> 00:05:14.380
, you have to sort of chisel out that figure.

00:05:14.380 --> 00:05:16.910
You have to take a screenshot of it, copy that data

00:05:16.910 --> 00:05:17.260
set.

00:05:17.260 --> 00:05:19.420
And as soon as you take it out of that piece of

00:05:19.420 --> 00:05:22.620
paper, that figure gets amnesia.

00:05:22.620 --> 00:05:26.180
It sort of forgets all about its attribution, its

00:05:26.180 --> 00:05:27.160
trust, its licensing.

00:05:27.180 --> 00:05:28.680
It loses its context.

00:05:28.700 --> 00:05:31.980
It loses like that license and that credit behind it.

00:05:31.980 --> 00:05:35.710
All of that rich metadata that sort of our scientific commons

00:05:35.710 --> 00:05:37.500
are designed to support.

00:05:37.500 --> 00:05:42.860
And so these were really the challenges that prompted the first wave

00:05:42.860 --> 00:05:44.010
of modular science.

00:05:44.060 --> 00:05:48.140
Many people recognize that it's not enough to share an advertisement

00:05:48.140 --> 00:05:49.640
of your experiment.

00:05:49.660 --> 00:05:53.110
You should share the data and the methods and the code underlying

00:05:53.220 --> 00:05:53.580
it.

00:05:55.020 --> 00:06:00.060
And so the prescription in 2010 was for modular science.

00:06:00.060 --> 00:06:00.860
It was pretty simple.

00:06:00.860 --> 00:06:04.140
You just break it into pieces and you put it into buckets

00:06:04.140 --> 00:06:04.140
.

00:06:04.140 --> 00:06:09.900
And you put it in the appropriate repository for that component.

00:06:09.900 --> 00:06:10.820
So protocols.

00:06:10.820 --> 00:06:12.380
io, you share your protocols.

00:06:12.380 --> 00:06:13.500
Figures go to fig share.

00:06:13.500 --> 00:06:16.780
Software heritage is the place that you share your code.

00:06:16.780 --> 00:06:20.860
A specialized data repository for genomics or microscopy data.

00:06:20.860 --> 00:06:23.380
And Zenodo can sort of take up all of the rest

00:06:23.380 --> 00:06:23.660
.

00:06:24.620 --> 00:06:28.060
And so these are the buckets of modular science.

00:06:28.060 --> 00:06:32.340
The digital repositories for archiving, tagging, organizing

00:06:32.340 --> 00:06:34.860
your data, protocols, code, and figures.

00:06:34.860 --> 00:06:39.140
And they really are actually excellent buckets.

00:06:39.180 --> 00:06:41.900
They exist fit for purpose for science.

00:06:41.900 --> 00:06:45.900
But they're largely designed for after the work is done.

00:06:45.900 --> 00:06:48.450
When you're starting to organize it, package it up,

00:06:48.460 --> 00:06:50.110
and put it in these places.

00:06:50.140 --> 00:06:53.980
So tidying up your workspace, putting the blocks away,

00:06:53.980 --> 00:06:57.890
and sort of pointing them from your glued together trophy on a

00:06:57.890 --> 00:06:58.300
shelf.

00:06:58.300 --> 00:07:01.410
And they're structured.

00:07:01.500 --> 00:07:02.300
They're organized.

00:07:02.300 --> 00:07:05.410
They strive to be these sort of tidy, curated spaces.

00:07:05.420 --> 00:07:08.110
And you fill out your intake form, specify your authors,

00:07:08.110 --> 00:07:10.370
license, description, your ORCID, your ROAR

00:07:10.370 --> 00:07:10.850
, your funders.

00:07:10.860 --> 00:07:12.440
All of these references.

00:07:12.460 --> 00:07:16.620
And it's really a very high bar to share work.

00:07:16.620 --> 00:07:22.410
And if you have some visualization code or a scratch script that

00:07:22.490 --> 00:07:26.650
you really know is the secret of how your work hangs together

00:07:26.650 --> 00:07:32.620
, it's like the bar for sharing that is so high

00:07:32.620 --> 00:07:33.180
.

00:07:33.180 --> 00:07:35.500
So all of those small things sort of get lost.

00:07:35.500 --> 00:07:39.700
They don't fit together on the shelf with that glued together

00:07:39.730 --> 00:07:40.540
trophy.

00:07:40.540 --> 00:07:44.820
And they don't really amount to enough to justify the investments

00:07:44.900 --> 00:07:47.340
to sort of formally request bucket status.

00:07:47.340 --> 00:07:52.860
And that's the aggregation of all of these small components

00:07:52.860 --> 00:07:55.740
of sort of the workflows and scripts of science fitting together.

00:07:55.740 --> 00:07:59.190
That's where the tacit knowledge of science lives of all

00:07:59.290 --> 00:08:03.380
of those workflow scripts of saying, yeah, I've seen

00:08:03.380 --> 00:08:04.140
that before.

00:08:04.140 --> 00:08:06.460
I'll grab you the notebook or I'll grab you that

00:08:06.460 --> 00:08:08.760
script or I've seen that last year and that's a

00:08:08.760 --> 00:08:09.240
dead end.

00:08:09.260 --> 00:08:14.620
And so these buckets are sort of both that very high bar

00:08:14.620 --> 00:08:18.380
and they're not fully aligned with science and with research,

00:08:18.380 --> 00:08:24.050
which is often much more much less structured than sort of the

00:08:24.050 --> 00:08:26.800
scientific method like laid out on a piece of paper step by

00:08:26.800 --> 00:08:27.100
step.

00:08:27.100 --> 00:08:28.590
That's that's how it works.

00:08:28.620 --> 00:08:30.890
It's much more fluid, much more serendipitous

00:08:30.890 --> 00:08:31.100
.

00:08:31.100 --> 00:08:34.460
You need to access all of the pieces to build new things

00:08:34.460 --> 00:08:37.340
and you sort of dump the buckets out onto the floor.

00:08:37.340 --> 00:08:41.730
And this this is the space to build, to experiment,

00:08:41.730 --> 00:08:45.020
to support that sort of serendipity of science.

00:08:45.020 --> 00:08:49.180
Maybe the equivalent of sort of leaving of that Petri dish

00:08:49.180 --> 00:08:52.700
out and Fleming discovering penicillin in 1928

00:08:52.700 --> 00:08:52.700
.

00:08:52.700 --> 00:08:57.560
Or maybe you have like slightly better lab hygiene protocols and setups

00:08:57.560 --> 00:09:01.340
and software so that you don't step on the pieces of

00:09:01.340 --> 00:09:04.770
Lego on the floor, but sort of have that goal to

00:09:04.830 --> 00:09:10.440
access those pieces readily and build them and put them together so

00:09:10.490 --> 00:09:14.050
that you can pull data from someone's lab in Tokyo,

00:09:14.060 --> 00:09:17.930
pull a protocol from Germany and remix them with your ideas to

00:09:17.930 --> 00:09:21.270
build something new, to learn something new, to discover something

00:09:21.370 --> 00:09:21.820
new.

00:09:21.820 --> 00:09:28.680
And so these these are the the three states of scientific components

00:09:28.680 --> 00:09:29.820
and modularity.

00:09:29.820 --> 00:09:32.160
They're on the floor, that chaos, that serend

00:09:32.160 --> 00:09:35.240
ipity, that remixing in the buckets organized by types

00:09:35.240 --> 00:09:38.450
, protocols, data, repositories, that's that first

00:09:38.450 --> 00:09:41.580
wave of modular science that was really tackling that problem.

00:09:41.580 --> 00:09:45.550
Or they're on the shelf, that composed artifact, that

00:09:45.570 --> 00:09:46.620
paper, that story.

00:09:46.620 --> 00:09:50.070
And all of these are are right.

00:09:50.170 --> 00:09:51.010
They're they're correct.

00:09:51.020 --> 00:09:54.470
They're like good ways that are fit for purpose for that

00:09:54.570 --> 00:09:54.860
task.

00:09:55.420 --> 00:09:57.880
And they're sort of that different side of that necr

00:09:57.880 --> 00:10:01.520
acube, that that illusion that flips and pops in and

00:10:01.560 --> 00:10:05.790
out for that right time that you need it for teaching or

00:10:05.790 --> 00:10:08.460
learning or discovering or building.

00:10:08.460 --> 00:10:14.570
And so I think this this is what the next wave of

00:10:14.850 --> 00:10:19.520
modular science is about, is not just sort of breaking it

00:10:19.520 --> 00:10:23.660
apart to share, which is sort of somewhat unnatural, especially

00:10:23.660 --> 00:10:26.980
if you have these sort of smaller artifacts that don't fit

00:10:26.980 --> 00:10:30.830
on a shelf sort of behind that trophy, is thinking about

00:10:30.900 --> 00:10:35.220
those sort of aggregate components that that are the connective space

00:10:35.220 --> 00:10:36.540
of science.

00:10:36.550 --> 00:10:39.870
And sharing those, there's such a high bar for for

00:10:39.870 --> 00:10:43.100
sharing those in in this sort of first wave.

00:10:43.100 --> 00:10:47.670
And it ends in this sort of disconnection, this constellation

00:10:47.670 --> 00:10:51.180
of research artifacts, where you have to tell a fable

00:10:51.180 --> 00:10:55.510
to imagine how it's all connected together, instead of actually

00:10:55.510 --> 00:10:57.010
connecting it together.

00:10:57.020 --> 00:11:02.730
And the second wave of modular science is about improving that packaging

00:11:02.730 --> 00:11:06.710
experience, working with the researcher as they're on the floor

00:11:06.710 --> 00:11:09.760
, as they're building, that is where the modularity

00:11:09.760 --> 00:11:10.430
emerges.

00:11:10.430 --> 00:11:13.970
You don't write a manuscript top to bottom 10,000

00:11:13.980 --> 00:11:17.360
unbroken words, one after another, with perfect figures,

00:11:17.360 --> 00:11:20.540
you iterate on the figures, you iterate one panel at a

00:11:20.540 --> 00:11:23.750
time, one script at a time, asking for feedback in

00:11:23.750 --> 00:11:28.200
this sort of modular composable way with with collaborators, and

00:11:28.220 --> 00:11:30.960
building up from that modular work.

00:11:30.980 --> 00:11:35.940
And it's a connected graph of discourse or computational narratives,

00:11:35.940 --> 00:11:39.580
supported by modern tooling like Obsidian or Mist Markdown,

00:11:39.580 --> 00:11:43.400
that can define the context of that data and how it travels

00:11:43.400 --> 00:11:44.250
together.

00:11:44.250 --> 00:11:47.590
And the result of all of this is sort of this multiplic

00:11:47.590 --> 00:11:51.480
ative additive compounding effect of how these things come together.

00:11:54.380 --> 00:11:58.720
And so I think it's also not worth losing sight of

00:11:58.740 --> 00:12:03.290
the end goal of this is actually to tell some of these

00:12:03.320 --> 00:12:04.250
new stories.

00:12:04.250 --> 00:12:07.140
These compositions are the point of science.

00:12:07.150 --> 00:12:10.760
And maybe we should aspirationally have these less be less like

00:12:10.820 --> 00:12:14.370
trophies on a shelf behind glass, but shared a little

00:12:14.380 --> 00:12:17.400
bit more continuously a little bit earlier.

00:12:17.410 --> 00:12:21.620
And here there's like this meta study that is crying out

00:12:21.630 --> 00:12:25.590
from here of how teapots are associated with the Lego

00:12:25.600 --> 00:12:28.550
bricks on the shelf that you actually want to pull these out

00:12:28.550 --> 00:12:30.780
and put them together and try something new.

00:12:30.780 --> 00:12:37.490
And so that that is like a very different thought of modular

00:12:37.490 --> 00:12:39.900
science than this first wave.

00:12:39.900 --> 00:12:43.230
So instead of thinking about the figures off on their own,

00:12:43.260 --> 00:12:47.440
we're thinking about the structure of these artifacts inside.

00:12:47.440 --> 00:12:51.340
So not import figure, but import figure from a paper.

00:12:51.340 --> 00:12:54.440
And that can compose all the way down so that you can

00:12:54.460 --> 00:12:58.990
get inside of these artifacts and bring modularity with you as

00:12:59.070 --> 00:13:01.180
it's traveling throughout the ecosystem.

00:13:05.260 --> 00:13:08.020
And so I, I just want to give a flavor of

00:13:08.020 --> 00:13:11.840
sort of the syntax of how we're thinking about, about

00:13:11.880 --> 00:13:15.260
modular science in this second wave.

00:13:15.260 --> 00:13:18.140
And it really does, I think the Lego metaphor works well

00:13:18.140 --> 00:13:22.710
here because it does have these specific ways that science fits together

00:13:22.730 --> 00:13:22.950
.

00:13:22.950 --> 00:13:26.620
This is the schemas and the standards and the pieces behind

00:13:26.620 --> 00:13:30.670
research of how they click together that you can make very different

00:13:30.860 --> 00:13:31.580
things.

00:13:31.580 --> 00:13:33.500
And there isn't glue here.

00:13:33.500 --> 00:13:36.780
You're also able to take them apart and put them into

00:13:36.780 --> 00:13:38.460
different compositions.

00:13:38.460 --> 00:13:42.880
And that is the goal of the project out of the Contin

00:13:42.880 --> 00:13:48.480
uous Science Foundation called Open Exchange Architecture, OXA or

00:13:48.480 --> 00:13:49.180
OXA.

00:13:49.180 --> 00:13:54.050
They are new standards for modular and composable scientific content.

00:13:54.070 --> 00:13:56.330
And you can learn more about that at OXA.

00:13:56.330 --> 00:13:57.320
dev.

00:13:57.320 --> 00:14:02.830
And this is a large project that's bringing together a lot

00:14:02.940 --> 00:14:07.740
of existing players in the scientific ecosystem, all the way from

00:14:07.750 --> 00:14:11.500
authoring tools like Korto or Mist Markdown that

00:14:11.500 --> 00:14:15.300
people might have started to use to publishers like eLife for

00:14:15.310 --> 00:14:19.340
traditional manuscripts or Open Archive for preprints, as well

00:14:19.340 --> 00:14:23.500
as licensing organizations like Creative Commons who are involved in sort of

00:14:23.500 --> 00:14:28.270
bringing all of these together into a modern computational, complete modular

00:14:28.270 --> 00:14:32.860
and composable format that can actually support our scientific narratives.

00:14:32.860 --> 00:14:37.990
And so some of the principles that we have for OX

00:14:38.000 --> 00:14:39.900
A is, of course, it's open.

00:14:39.900 --> 00:14:43.180
It's a JSON schema-based representation.

00:14:43.180 --> 00:14:47.730
It's a tree-based representation of the scientific content specifically

00:14:47.730 --> 00:14:47.920
.

00:14:47.920 --> 00:14:50.940
And so this is anything from the paragraph, citations,

00:14:50.940 --> 00:14:52.950
figures, equations, or code.

00:14:52.950 --> 00:14:56.220
It is extensible to these sort of new types of data

00:14:56.230 --> 00:14:59.470
, composable so that you can bring one person's work

00:14:59.470 --> 00:15:02.930
and compose it inside of yours, typed down, very similar

00:15:02.930 --> 00:15:06.010
to the sort of the at proto schemas, and thinking

00:15:06.010 --> 00:15:09.090
about that interoperability modularity.

00:15:09.090 --> 00:15:13.950
And throughout all of this, really thinking about the computation as

00:15:13.950 --> 00:15:17.400
a first class citizen within this schema itself.

00:15:17.420 --> 00:15:22.870
It's also going through, we're thinking at this stage

00:15:22.880 --> 00:15:26.050
a lot about the governance and how we're actually building this

00:15:26.050 --> 00:15:26.360
up.

00:15:26.360 --> 00:15:29.230
And so there's an RFC process that actually goes through

00:15:29.280 --> 00:15:32.440
and we're beginning this movement, I think, in the

00:15:32.440 --> 00:15:35.580
right way from that perspective, so that we're actually building

00:15:35.580 --> 00:15:38.300
this up and being fit for purpose all the way through.

00:15:38.300 --> 00:15:43.340
And it also, of course, has an at proto recognition

00:15:43.340 --> 00:15:44.120
on that.

00:15:44.120 --> 00:15:49.430
So you can transfer out of this much more schema, sorry

00:15:49.430 --> 00:15:52.320
, tree-based schema, which is sort of the native

00:15:52.320 --> 00:15:55.390
representation of OXA, to something that's a little

00:15:55.390 --> 00:15:58.750
closer to what at proto works with, which is a fac

00:15:58.750 --> 00:16:01.970
et-based piece where you can actually have some of those

00:16:01.980 --> 00:16:06.140
annotations, which might be a citation or an additional abbrevi

00:16:06.140 --> 00:16:10.390
ation or something that is deeply nested inside of this schema

00:16:10.390 --> 00:16:13.720
, but can be distributed from sort of a social perspective.

00:16:13.720 --> 00:16:16.540
And so there's a lot of thought going in here.

00:16:16.540 --> 00:16:18.620
And this is definitely early stages.

00:16:18.620 --> 00:16:22.380
And so we're inviting a lot of people to come,

00:16:22.380 --> 00:16:25.480
be involved in sort of the definition of the schema as it

00:16:25.480 --> 00:16:26.660
starts to exist.

00:16:26.660 --> 00:16:31.380
And I want to just give a couple different flavors with my

00:16:31.440 --> 00:16:34.240
Curvenote hat on about some of the case studies that

00:16:34.260 --> 00:16:37.340
we're bringing to bear with these ideas.

00:16:37.340 --> 00:16:41.880
And so this Elemental Microscopy is a journal that

00:16:41.880 --> 00:16:44.830
we're working with that's trying to do something a little

00:16:44.830 --> 00:16:48.840
bit more exciting than just sort of a picture on a page

00:16:48.880 --> 00:16:52.740
with a blowout of that sort of one and a half

00:16:52.790 --> 00:16:56.750
terabytes of data is you should actually be able, similar

00:16:56.750 --> 00:17:00.370
to Google Maps, to just like zoom into it directly as

00:17:00.370 --> 00:17:03.580
you're reading, is we have all of these sorts of

00:17:03.580 --> 00:17:05.810
visuals out there already.

00:17:05.810 --> 00:17:08.170
Scientists are using them in their day-to-day work

00:17:08.170 --> 00:17:08.330
.

00:17:08.330 --> 00:17:11.340
So we should be able to compose those into the ways that

00:17:11.340 --> 00:17:13.070
we are sharing science.

00:17:13.070 --> 00:17:16.460
And this is speaking to that modularity as well.

00:17:16.460 --> 00:17:19.800
That one and a half terabytes doesn't live inside of

00:17:19.800 --> 00:17:20.530
the paper.

00:17:20.530 --> 00:17:23.960
It does live in its appropriate bucket, but it can be

00:17:23.960 --> 00:17:28.530
composed into the way that we share and read and communicate science

00:17:28.530 --> 00:17:28.780
.

00:17:28.780 --> 00:17:32.720
So thinking about not a constellation of research objects that we're

00:17:32.720 --> 00:17:35.760
sort of painting the stars, but actually showing you how it

00:17:35.760 --> 00:17:36.620
all fits together.

00:17:41.020 --> 00:17:44.700
The other project that's one of the other projects that Cur

00:17:44.700 --> 00:17:48.090
venote is working on is a partnership with Open Archive

00:17:48.090 --> 00:17:48.320
.

00:17:48.320 --> 00:17:52.360
Open Archive is the parent organization around Bio Archive and

00:17:52.360 --> 00:17:56.570
Med Archive, which are the largest biomedical preprint servers

00:17:56.570 --> 00:17:56.820
.

00:17:56.850 --> 00:17:59.890
And we are currently reprocessing 8.

00:18:00.020 --> 00:18:04.220
1 terabytes of articles to this new format.

00:18:04.220 --> 00:18:06.620
And so this is something that's ongoing right now.

00:18:06.620 --> 00:18:09.260
There's about half a million preprints that are coming together

00:18:09.260 --> 00:18:09.260
.

00:18:09.270 --> 00:18:15.720
And this is going to support more exciting reading experiences where you

00:18:15.720 --> 00:18:18.360
can hover over a figure and bring that in.

00:18:18.360 --> 00:18:20.060
You can dive into that right away.

00:18:20.060 --> 00:18:24.440
And so this is within the context of a single article that

00:18:24.440 --> 00:18:28.770
you can bring that modular piece to bear in the context and

00:18:28.770 --> 00:18:31.570
bring that sort of forward in your way of working.

00:18:31.570 --> 00:18:40.340
But that also should be able to exist across

00:18:40.340 --> 00:18:41.640
research articles.

00:18:41.680 --> 00:18:44.850
And so some research articles, if you hover over them,

00:18:44.860 --> 00:18:47.320
are closed access and they're not that exciting.

00:18:47.340 --> 00:18:49.860
But if they're open access or a preprint, you

00:18:49.860 --> 00:18:53.140
should be able to bring the figure from that to bear right

00:18:53.140 --> 00:18:54.380
as you're reading.

00:18:54.400 --> 00:18:58.470
And so really thinking again about this sort of modular composable

00:18:58.470 --> 00:19:02.940
way of working that really can improve both the reading experience of

00:19:02.940 --> 00:19:03.900
a researcher.

00:19:03.900 --> 00:19:07.650
Like if if you have a reference that says see figure three

00:19:07.660 --> 00:19:11.240
in someone at all, like you have to scroll to the

00:19:11.260 --> 00:19:13.500
bottom of the page, download the PDF, jump through a

00:19:13.500 --> 00:19:16.280
paywall, bring it up in your reference manager, scroll

00:19:16.280 --> 00:19:20.610
to page 50 and actually get the the figure there.

00:19:20.620 --> 00:19:23.410
And by the time you've got there, you've lost

00:19:23.420 --> 00:19:26.870
all of your context and machines often can't follow all of

00:19:26.970 --> 00:19:29.210
that work either.

00:19:29.250 --> 00:19:33.330
And so this, this I think is thinking about that sort

00:19:33.330 --> 00:19:36.620
of next wave of modular science, both from the user experience

00:19:36.710 --> 00:19:40.480
standpoint, the schemas that are supporting it, as well

00:19:40.480 --> 00:19:44.200
as the ways that sort of the community can get involved throughout

00:19:44.200 --> 00:19:44.380
.

00:19:44.380 --> 00:19:51.150
And so not thinking about trophies on a shelf that are

00:19:51.150 --> 00:19:54.130
glued together, but pieces that you can take.

00:19:54.130 --> 00:19:59.650
And those are a starting point for the next analysis, lowering

00:19:59.670 --> 00:20:03.820
the barrier to entry for inclusion in these buckets that you can

00:20:03.820 --> 00:20:07.520
maybe package these up with the pieces that you are sharing and

00:20:07.520 --> 00:20:10.460
still be indexed in, in these different ways, as

00:20:10.470 --> 00:20:14.990
well as supporting researchers as they're working on the floor with

00:20:14.990 --> 00:20:19.450
better tooling, better graph based waves of working better computational notebooks

00:20:19.450 --> 00:20:23.590
that actually support the organization and communication of all of these results

00:20:23.590 --> 00:20:23.730
.

00:20:23.740 --> 00:20:27.680
And so that is, I think the way this new wave

00:20:27.680 --> 00:20:32.010
of modular science is not saying one of these ways of working

00:20:32.020 --> 00:20:35.140
is better than the other, but it's flipping that perspective

00:20:35.170 --> 00:20:39.370
back and forth between all of these different ways of working all

00:20:39.370 --> 00:20:39.800
at once.

00:20:39.820 --> 00:20:45.900
And so I think the other really exciting piece that was talked

00:20:45.900 --> 00:20:49.290
about at the start as well is this is our time.

00:20:49.290 --> 00:20:52.860
This is our semblance of this space and there is so

00:20:52.860 --> 00:20:56.820
much going on that we can actually affect massive change in the

00:20:56.820 --> 00:20:58.380
way that science is done.

00:20:58.380 --> 00:21:00.940
So I am Groen Cockett.

00:21:00.940 --> 00:21:02.520
I'm the CEO of Curvenote and also one of

00:21:02.540 --> 00:21:06.370
the co-founders of Continuous Science Foundation and follow

00:21:06.400 --> 00:21:07.820
me on Blue Sky.

00:21:07.820 --> 00:21:09.740
So thank you very much.

00:21:09.740 --> 00:21:15.580
- Thank you very much.

00:21:16.070 --> 00:21:19.580
- Thank you.

00:21:20.070 --> 00:21:25.580
- I think we're doing a few times before.

00:21:26.130 --> 00:21:29.580
- Thank you.

00:21:30.070 --> 00:21:31.580
- Thank you.

00:21:32.070 --> 00:21:33.580
- Thank you.

00:21:33.590 --> 00:21:42.910
- Hello, yes

00:21:42.910 --> 00:21:51.380
, great.

00:21:51.910 --> 00:21:53.420
- Hello, yes.

00:21:53.910 --> 00:21:55.420
- Great.

00:21:55.910 --> 00:22:11.420
- - -

00:22:11.420 --> 00:22:19.950
Well, thank you

00:22:19.950 --> 00:22:23.260
, Rowan, for such an inspiring talk.

00:22:23.260 --> 00:22:27.400
Rowan and I first met about this time last year at

00:22:27.420 --> 00:22:32.210
a Continuous Science Foundation workshop that Rowan organized in Ban

00:22:32.210 --> 00:22:36.460
ff in which we converged at this idea of modular research

00:22:36.460 --> 00:22:39.420
as a new paradigm for open science.

00:22:39.420 --> 00:22:43.380
And so I'll show today how our research lab at the

00:22:43.380 --> 00:22:48.770
University of Washington uses modular science principles for interoperable and

00:22:48.780 --> 00:22:51.330
extensible open research practices.

00:22:54.690 --> 00:22:59.010
- Why don't I turn this down a little bit?

00:22:59.010 --> 00:22:59.820
There's a little bit of an echo.

00:22:59.830 --> 00:23:07.010
Or is it this?

00:23:07.020 --> 00:23:09.180
Turn that off.

00:23:09.180 --> 00:23:10.130
Better?

00:23:10.220 --> 00:23:10.700
Better.

00:23:10.700 --> 00:23:10.940
Yes.

00:23:10.940 --> 00:23:13.490
So my name is Matt Akamatsu.

00:23:13.500 --> 00:23:16.370
I'm an assistant professor of biology at the University of Washington

00:23:16.380 --> 00:23:16.380
.

00:23:17.020 --> 00:23:21.590
And today I'll show how discourse graphs help our labs to

00:23:21.660 --> 00:23:25.900
enable modular and interoperable research practices.

00:23:25.900 --> 00:23:30.420
So I started my lab at the University of Washington about three

00:23:30.420 --> 00:23:31.420
and a half years ago.

00:23:31.420 --> 00:23:32.860
Here we are on the right.

00:23:32.860 --> 00:23:35.800
And I've also co-founded the discourse graphs project,

00:23:35.800 --> 00:23:40.390
which is an open science and collaboration, tooling, software development

00:23:40.490 --> 00:23:42.620
platform, and organization.

00:23:42.620 --> 00:23:47.700
And through these two organizations, we design, build, and

00:23:47.740 --> 00:23:53.020
test new ways to do scientific research that enables better, faster

00:23:53.070 --> 00:23:58.700
research collaboration and sharing of our research outputs in real time.

00:23:58.700 --> 00:24:03.660
These projects are motivated by many of the systemic barriers to research

00:24:03.670 --> 00:24:08.820
collaboration that Rowan just described that have been exacerbated now

00:24:08.820 --> 00:24:14.430
that generative AI is a regular participant in the scientific research

00:24:14.460 --> 00:24:15.500
and publishing process.

00:24:15.500 --> 00:24:21.610
That is best exemplified by this scandal that broke out sometime

00:24:21.630 --> 00:24:26.590
last year in the International Conference on Learning Representations, where

00:24:26.640 --> 00:24:31.070
it became apparent that the majority of, or many of the

00:24:31.070 --> 00:24:36.700
submissions as well as reviews for this conference, for these conference

00:24:36.700 --> 00:24:41.400
papers on machine learning, were entirely generated by low-quality

00:24:41.400 --> 00:24:43.420
AI that didn't make any sense.

00:24:43.420 --> 00:24:48.380
And so that caused this researcher to say we're entering an

00:24:48.380 --> 00:24:51.670
era in which distinguishing real science science from low-quality

00:24:51.670 --> 00:24:52.690
AI will be essential.

00:24:52.690 --> 00:24:59.970
An AI tool did an analysis of these reviews and submissions that

00:25:00.060 --> 00:25:05.540
indicated that over 20% of the submissions were entirely AI-

00:25:05.540 --> 00:25:09.800
generated and another large percentage of them were moderately AI

00:25:09.800 --> 00:25:10.880
-generated.

00:25:10.880 --> 00:25:14.380
And so it says it seems that 21% of these reviews

00:25:14.380 --> 00:25:15.180
may be AI.

00:25:15.180 --> 00:25:18.630
But that leads to the same type of question, how strongly

00:25:18.730 --> 00:25:23.020
should we trust this particular report and this tool?

00:25:23.020 --> 00:25:25.380
So the caveat, LLM-generated text detection

00:25:25.380 --> 00:25:26.140
is not perfect.

00:25:26.140 --> 00:25:31.350
So this is illustrating that we need some better grounded piece

00:25:31.350 --> 00:25:35.230
of information, some evidence to help us to weigh how much

00:25:35.240 --> 00:25:39.420
we should trust this measurement and by extension how much we should

00:25:39.420 --> 00:25:45.060
trust these scientific research submissions that up until now have been the

00:25:45.110 --> 00:25:49.340
substrate for how you share your research communication.

00:25:49.340 --> 00:25:52.860
But that's under tremendous strain because of large language models.

00:25:52.860 --> 00:25:56.910
So we wonder, in this day and age, what is

00:25:56.910 --> 00:26:02.400
the appropriate source code for scientific communication in the age of AI

00:26:02.470 --> 00:26:02.860
?

00:26:02.860 --> 00:26:05.430
And I pose this question tongue-in-cheek because

00:26:05.470 --> 00:26:07.730
, as many of you know, the role of source code

00:26:07.730 --> 00:26:11.820
itself has changed quite a bit over the past year in programming

00:26:11.840 --> 00:26:15.390
because it now can be freely generated by AI and regenerated

00:26:15.390 --> 00:26:17.660
from specific instructions.

00:26:17.660 --> 00:26:23.480
So we expect the same transformation may occur for scientific research communication

00:26:23.480 --> 00:26:25.820
, where up until now the state-of-the-

00:26:25.840 --> 00:26:30.420
art has been this long-form narrative PDF that's dozens

00:26:30.420 --> 00:26:34.460
of pages long, compiles five years worth of work,

00:26:34.460 --> 00:26:38.460
and several dozen results into this single document with a linear auth

00:26:38.470 --> 00:26:39.420
orship list.

00:26:39.430 --> 00:26:44.170
Likely, we'll need some other substrate for communicating our

00:26:44.170 --> 00:26:47.740
research that is smaller than this long-form journal PDF,

00:26:47.740 --> 00:26:52.190
but larger than the individual raw data or text.

00:26:52.190 --> 00:26:56.880
And our principles of operation, as Rowan introduced, are

00:26:56.940 --> 00:27:00.860
that we'd like this system to be reusable so that we

00:27:00.880 --> 00:27:05.840
can build upon different elements of the research process and synthesize

00:27:05.840 --> 00:27:10.300
them into living theories of knowledge about our favorite corner of the

00:27:10.300 --> 00:27:11.780
natural world.

00:27:11.780 --> 00:27:16.200
We need each element to have clear provenance and attribution

00:27:16.220 --> 00:27:18.960
, and we'd love for it to center human decision-

00:27:18.960 --> 00:27:24.140
making in an era when the AI scientists are getting increasingly powerful

00:27:24.140 --> 00:27:24.440
.

00:27:24.440 --> 00:27:28.640
Absent a deliberate design for collaboration, we might find ourselves

00:27:28.640 --> 00:27:31.420
out of a job for the fun parts of doing science.

00:27:31.430 --> 00:27:35.620
Therefore, our goal is to decouple research into modular

00:27:35.620 --> 00:27:39.840
elements that each can be reused, cited, and synthes

00:27:39.840 --> 00:27:40.440
ized.

00:27:40.500 --> 00:27:45.670
Those atomic elements are questions, claims, and evidence, which

00:27:45.670 --> 00:27:46.780
we connect into a graph.

00:27:46.780 --> 00:27:51.300
This data model comes from the science philosopher Stephen Tullman

00:27:51.340 --> 00:27:56.540
, who argues that science is less a series of monolithic

00:27:56.540 --> 00:28:00.090
truths and more a series of claims that are supported by more

00:28:00.090 --> 00:28:01.420
or less evidence.

00:28:01.420 --> 00:28:03.930
And over time, you gather more evidence, some of the

00:28:03.930 --> 00:28:05.700
claims go away and new claims arise.

00:28:05.710 --> 00:28:08.520
And so we'd like to be able to capture not only

00:28:08.520 --> 00:28:11.110
the claims, but the evidence that supports them so that we

00:28:11.110 --> 00:28:11.960
can update them.

00:28:11.980 --> 00:28:15.960
And this particular project is the product of a five and a

00:28:15.960 --> 00:28:21.790
half year collaboration between myself and human computer interaction researcher Joelle

00:28:21.790 --> 00:28:23.900
Chan at the University of Maryland.

00:28:23.900 --> 00:28:27.880
And together, we build both the information model and plugins to

00:28:27.880 --> 00:28:32.100
popular note-taking software so that we can run our labs

00:28:32.220 --> 00:28:38.270
on this modular research paradigm and test what works, what genuinely

00:28:38.270 --> 00:28:40.850
helps the advancement of our lab's research.

00:28:40.860 --> 00:28:44.280
So to this end, we've built discourse graphs, which

00:28:44.280 --> 00:28:47.670
are both a protocol and an app for interoperable knowledge

00:28:47.670 --> 00:28:48.200
exchange.

00:28:48.220 --> 00:28:50.540
Here's the information model.

00:28:50.540 --> 00:28:55.190
We take our scientific arguments and projects and decouple them

00:28:55.190 --> 00:28:59.170
into questions, claims and evidence and connect them into a graph

00:28:59.170 --> 00:28:59.500
.

00:28:59.500 --> 00:29:03.540
The question is the unknown that you'd like to make known

00:29:03.540 --> 00:29:05.160
with your research project.

00:29:05.160 --> 00:29:08.680
The claim is the current answer to the research question, which

00:29:08.680 --> 00:29:11.860
it wants to be supported by one or more lines of evidence

00:29:11.860 --> 00:29:12.110
.

00:29:12.110 --> 00:29:17.390
Each piece of evidence is a specific observation from your work with

00:29:17.390 --> 00:29:21.900
an outcome and it's grounded in a single study or experiment

00:29:21.900 --> 00:29:24.710
or at least a published research article.

00:29:24.710 --> 00:29:26.900
The article grounds the evidence.

00:29:26.910 --> 00:29:30.620
The evidence supports or opposes the claim and the claim,

00:29:30.620 --> 00:29:35.280
when incomplete, always motivates a new experiment that you want to

00:29:35.280 --> 00:29:38.300
do driving the research research cycle forward.

00:29:38.300 --> 00:29:41.180
I'll give a historical example.

00:29:41.180 --> 00:29:46.830
70 years ago, there were two competing claims for what is

00:29:46.830 --> 00:29:49.650
the three-dimensional structure of DNA.

00:29:49.650 --> 00:29:52.070
Is it a double helix or is it a triple hel

00:29:52.070 --> 00:29:52.480
ix?

00:29:52.520 --> 00:29:56.710
Where are the negatively charged phosphates in this DNA helix

00:29:56.710 --> 00:29:57.020
?

00:29:57.020 --> 00:30:02.230
And there was no evidence to distinguish between these two competing claims

00:30:02.270 --> 00:30:05.890
until Rosalind Franklin's famous x-ray diffraction

00:30:05.990 --> 00:30:11.900
experiment showed this very characteristic diffraction pattern that gave us some

00:30:11.900 --> 00:30:16.220
information about what the spacing is likely to be between these DNA

00:30:16.230 --> 00:30:23.420
bases and that supported the double helix model for the structure

00:30:23.420 --> 00:30:24.430
of DNA.

00:30:24.530 --> 00:30:29.630
So in this discourse graphs framing, Rosalind Franklin could

00:30:29.700 --> 00:30:34.850
have posted this single result to the group, to the group

00:30:34.850 --> 00:30:37.620
's personal data server, I suppose, and said, "

00:30:37.670 --> 00:30:38.940
This is a result.

00:30:38.940 --> 00:30:40.500
It's reproducible.

00:30:40.500 --> 00:30:42.780
I'm going to show you -- I'm going to tell

00:30:42.780 --> 00:30:43.920
you the observation.

00:30:43.920 --> 00:30:45.970
I'm going to tell you the -- I'm going to

00:30:45.970 --> 00:30:49.530
give you the associated figure and a little methods context.

00:30:49.580 --> 00:30:51.940
Let's figure out what it means together." And in order

00:30:51.940 --> 00:30:55.940
to strengthen their claim that DNA has a double helix structure

00:30:55.940 --> 00:30:59.450
, Watson and Crick would have needed to cite Franklin's

00:30:59.450 --> 00:31:00.840
piece of evidence.

00:31:00.880 --> 00:31:03.730
Otherwise, it would remain an untested claim.

00:31:03.730 --> 00:31:07.410
And what I love about this model is that it creates an

00:31:07.410 --> 00:31:14.600
automatic attribution structure that appropriately credits Franklin's contribution to this

00:31:14.600 --> 00:31:19.580
discovery over the course of just making a stronger scientific argument.

00:31:19.580 --> 00:31:25.050
Alternatively, in a world absent evidence, the modelers could

00:31:25.190 --> 00:31:29.420
instead request that somebody do this DNA diffraction experiment because it

00:31:29.420 --> 00:31:31.150
's important for their model.

00:31:31.150 --> 00:31:34.390
And then some -- an experimentalist might claim that experiment,

00:31:34.390 --> 00:31:36.540
carry it out, tell them what the result was.

00:31:37.260 --> 00:31:41.240
And then the modelers get some credit for their intellectual contribution

00:31:41.250 --> 00:31:42.050
to the idea.

00:31:42.070 --> 00:31:46.460
And the experimentalists get their credit for doing the work.

00:31:46.460 --> 00:31:49.740
In both cases, the attribution trail isn't some after

00:31:49.740 --> 00:31:51.150
-the-fact accounting.

00:31:51.150 --> 00:31:54.460
Instead, it's baked into the ongoing research process.

00:31:54.460 --> 00:31:58.620
So we got very excited about this model and whether it might

00:31:58.620 --> 00:32:04.810
support our researchers' everyday work and also allow for this natural

00:32:04.810 --> 00:32:08.380
sort of self-organizing system for modular science.

00:32:08.460 --> 00:32:12.740
So we've spent the last number of years developing open source

00:32:12.740 --> 00:32:15.910
plug-ins for some of our favorite note-taking apps

00:32:15.910 --> 00:32:20.060
like Obsidian or Rome Research in which I'm presenting in

00:32:20.060 --> 00:32:24.190
order to make life easier for the researchers in our labs.

00:32:24.190 --> 00:32:27.330
These plug-ins help grad students, postdocs,

00:32:27.360 --> 00:32:32.210
undergraduates to orient their projects in context with open questions and

00:32:32.210 --> 00:32:36.270
key hypotheses and keep them on track towards the question that they

00:32:36.270 --> 00:32:38.170
decided they wanted to answer.

00:32:38.170 --> 00:32:41.870
It allows them to inventory super early stage results as soon as

00:32:41.870 --> 00:32:45.520
they think they might have an observation and share them with the

00:32:45.520 --> 00:32:49.380
team every week in our group meetings and then synthesize those

00:32:49.380 --> 00:32:55.620
results into scientific arguments and scientific stories in context with the published

00:32:55.620 --> 00:33:00.930
literature so that they have rigorous and updatable stories of the

00:33:00.930 --> 00:33:03.740
state of knowledge for their research field.

00:33:03.740 --> 00:33:08.480
And so we've found that running our labs on this information

00:33:08.480 --> 00:33:14.580
model has enabled large-scale collaboration, coordination, and sense

00:33:14.610 --> 00:33:18.010
-making among members of our lab.

00:33:18.010 --> 00:33:22.910
So here's a couple examples showing how using discourse graphs as

00:33:22.910 --> 00:33:28.460
our lab's graph-based shared lab notebook and meetings documentation

00:33:28.460 --> 00:33:33.390
and storyboard for our manuscripts and stories has led to a

00:33:33.400 --> 00:33:39.160
richly interconnected graph of questions, claims, claims, and

00:33:39.160 --> 00:33:41.010
