00:33:56.110 --> 00:34:01.740
half years of our lab's creation, which shows how around

00:34:01.740 --> 00:34:08.380
3,500 of these cross-author references have been generated

00:34:08.410 --> 00:34:12.380
, indicating that we are building off of each other's intellectual

00:34:12.380 --> 00:34:13.570
work in real time.

00:34:13.580 --> 00:34:16.720
This is both evidence from the published literature as well as new

00:34:16.720 --> 00:34:20.520
evidence from our ongoing experiments and simulations.

00:34:20.520 --> 00:34:24.080
And we're even building theories of knowledge where one person's

00:34:24.080 --> 00:34:27.340
evidence supports somebody else's hypothesis.

00:34:27.340 --> 00:34:33.790
Here's another example showing that we're not only sharing knowledge

00:34:33.890 --> 00:34:38.140
, but we're also distributing the work, the requested experiments

00:34:38.160 --> 00:34:38.420
.

00:34:38.460 --> 00:34:44.900
In this plot we show the transfer of a requested experiment.

00:34:44.900 --> 00:34:49.410
Somebody says, "You know, this analysis experiment is a

00:34:49.420 --> 00:34:49.980
good idea.

00:34:49.980 --> 00:34:51.290
Somebody should do it.

00:34:51.290 --> 00:34:53.330
I don't have time to do it right now, but

00:34:53.330 --> 00:34:56.260
either me in the future or an undergraduate will come in,

00:34:56.260 --> 00:34:58.690
see this dashboard, claim it, and say, "This

00:34:58.720 --> 00:35:02.380
is how I can contribute to important problems in the lab."

00:35:02.380 --> 00:35:08.030
And so this diagram shows how the transfer of experiments that were

00:35:08.030 --> 00:35:11.860
requested and then claimed, often by a different person in the

00:35:11.860 --> 00:35:16.650
lab, and some of which culminate in a new observation

00:35:16.700 --> 00:35:18.140
that completes the experiment.

00:35:18.140 --> 00:35:19.020
I have the result.

00:35:19.030 --> 00:35:20.060
I have the analysis.

00:35:20.060 --> 00:35:21.500
Here's the outcome.

00:35:21.500 --> 00:35:24.220
We can close this issue.

00:35:25.020 --> 00:35:28.820
And so this show, and the other thing I love about

00:35:28.840 --> 00:35:34.610
this transfer is that a number of these posts and claiming and

00:35:34.640 --> 00:35:38.700
completion of experiments were done entirely without my knowledge until they were

00:35:38.720 --> 00:35:42.300
completed, which as the principal investigator gives me a lot of

00:35:42.300 --> 00:35:45.610
assurance that researchers are getting the mentorship that they need from each

00:35:45.610 --> 00:35:50.250
other, finding important work to do, and having a very

00:35:50.250 --> 00:35:53.530
clear trail of who did the work work in a self-

00:35:53.530 --> 00:35:55.890
organizing fashion.

00:35:55.900 --> 00:35:59.630
So in this case, something like 30% of these issues

00:35:59.630 --> 00:36:02.630
, requests for experiments, were claimed.

00:36:02.730 --> 00:36:05.100
40% of them yielded a result, and 15%

00:36:05.100 --> 00:36:07.820
of those happened between different lab members.

00:36:09.260 --> 00:36:13.220
So with this proof of concept within our own labs, we

00:36:13.220 --> 00:36:17.330
now seek to bring these tools in a pilot program to other

00:36:17.420 --> 00:36:19.170
research labs throughout North America.

00:36:19.170 --> 00:36:23.610
So we're halfway through a user pilot supported by the Chan

00:36:23.740 --> 00:36:28.020
Zuckerberg Initiative and the Navigation Fund, in which we

00:36:28.020 --> 00:36:32.660
develop these plugins so that they are easy to use for these

00:36:32.660 --> 00:36:38.380
research labs and organizations so that they may better track their experiments

00:36:38.380 --> 00:36:43.330
, post research updates, and synthesize their work into their

00:36:43.350 --> 00:36:45.420
ongoing manuscripts, etc.

00:36:45.420 --> 00:36:50.410
What we found so far is that these discourse graphs help researchers

00:36:50.420 --> 00:36:54.640
, for example, synthesize results into scientific stories in context

00:36:54.640 --> 00:36:55.980
with the literature.

00:36:55.980 --> 00:37:00.230
First, in this non-linear format, akin to the

00:37:00.240 --> 00:37:03.780
floor of Lego bricks that Rowan just described, here we

00:37:03.790 --> 00:37:08.550
're looking at an open canvas where the researcher in Obsidian

00:37:08.550 --> 00:37:15.780
can share these individual experiments, results, meaning evidence, and

00:37:15.980 --> 00:37:21.070
claims in this open graph along with whatever notes he might want

00:37:21.070 --> 00:37:26.740
to include and connect them into this non-linear graph.

00:37:26.740 --> 00:37:31.020
He calls this his murder board or his whodunit

00:37:31.020 --> 00:37:37.020
pertaining to his research question that is grounded in the individual evidence

00:37:37.020 --> 00:37:41.660
from the literature and from his ongoing experimental observations.

00:37:41.660 --> 00:37:45.260
And he uses it to plan what is the right experiment to

00:37:45.260 --> 00:37:49.680
do next and communicate to the rest of his lab what his

00:37:49.720 --> 00:37:50.680
findings are.

00:37:50.720 --> 00:37:54.760
We're making it possible for him to share individual results with

00:37:54.790 --> 00:37:59.910
collaborators or wider networks of researchers, but it's also possible

00:37:59.910 --> 00:38:05.500
to compile these individual results into a figure for a traditional manuscript

00:38:05.500 --> 00:38:08.510
if that's what you need to do.

00:38:08.530 --> 00:38:11.710
So here's an example from our lab where an undergraduate is

00:38:11.710 --> 00:38:15.750
compiling the figures for his manuscript starting with the question.

00:38:15.750 --> 00:38:19.570
Each panel of the figure corresponds to one piece of evidence.

00:38:19.570 --> 00:38:22.740
It's an observation that you put there because it's strengthening

00:38:22.740 --> 00:38:25.540
your overall claim that you're trying to make in the figure

00:38:25.570 --> 00:38:25.820
.

00:38:25.820 --> 00:38:30.300
So using discourse graphs demystifies the process of compiling

00:38:30.300 --> 00:38:35.100
or recompiling your scientific narrative from the underlying evidence.

00:38:35.100 --> 00:38:40.470
We've found so far that discourse graphs help researchers in the

00:38:40.480 --> 00:38:43.580
pilot labs and in our own labs to do the following.

00:38:43.580 --> 00:38:46.260
It helps them think like a scientist.

00:38:46.260 --> 00:38:50.190
People report through qualitative research that we're doing with Joelle

00:38:50.190 --> 00:38:54.160
's lab that they have found huge improvements in their thinking and

00:38:54.160 --> 00:38:55.260
doing of science.

00:38:55.260 --> 00:38:58.540
And even when they're not using the plug-in,

00:38:58.540 --> 00:39:00.690
it helps keep them in the frame of mind.

00:39:00.720 --> 00:39:03.860
They call it the discourse graphs frame of mind where they remember

00:39:03.860 --> 00:39:07.630
their goal is to be addressing questions by providing evidence that supports

00:39:07.630 --> 00:39:09.260
or opposes their hypotheses.

00:39:09.260 --> 00:39:13.260
It also helps them feel like a scientist, saying that they

00:39:13.260 --> 00:39:18.140
now have the confidence to share a result without having to claim

00:39:18.140 --> 00:39:20.730
that they have the be-all end-all interpretation of

00:39:20.730 --> 00:39:21.390
that result.

00:39:21.440 --> 00:39:22.920
They say this is the observation.

00:39:22.920 --> 00:39:24.940
Let's all figure out together what you think it means.

00:39:24.940 --> 00:39:26.590
I'm just an undergraduate.

00:39:26.630 --> 00:39:29.220
And so now they have the confidence to share their results much

00:39:29.220 --> 00:39:33.340
earlier than they would have otherwise given that they're sharing it

00:39:33.340 --> 00:39:36.860
within a trusted environment of their lab or their collaborators.

00:39:36.860 --> 00:39:41.970
Here's another researcher saying that now I have a motivation because

00:39:41.980 --> 00:39:45.090
I feel like I have permission to use the words "hy

00:39:45.090 --> 00:39:49.900
pothesis" supporting my hypotheses because they're now baked

00:39:49.900 --> 00:39:52.690
into the way that I'm sharing my work.

00:39:52.690 --> 00:39:56.330
So now I can use those words and that makes it much

00:39:56.330 --> 00:39:59.670
easier and makes me feel like I'm a scientist.

00:39:59.670 --> 00:40:02.290
And so it feels like it's true progress where I'm

00:40:02.290 --> 00:40:05.870
not just sort of collecting data, but I'm generating novel

00:40:05.910 --> 00:40:09.180
observations instead of just where do I start.

00:40:09.180 --> 00:40:13.040
And very excitingly, we have an early indication that some

00:40:13.080 --> 00:40:18.540
researchers feel that documenting their research in discourse graphs better reflects the

00:40:18.540 --> 00:40:22.340
true nature of doing science than writing up narratives and making slides

00:40:22.360 --> 00:40:22.820
hows.

00:40:22.820 --> 00:40:26.350
So they say converting to this kind of structure is maybe more

00:40:26.350 --> 00:40:30.420
aligned with what the actual process is like of answering research questions

00:40:30.420 --> 00:40:34.060
that can be complementary to writing up your long-form narratives

00:40:34.080 --> 00:40:37.950
, but may end up being more useful and truer to

00:40:37.990 --> 00:40:42.380
the way that the process of science that people actually want to

00:40:42.390 --> 00:40:45.740
be carrying out, particularly in collaborations.

00:40:45.740 --> 00:40:52.610
I'm also excited about how having this modular graph structure makes

00:40:52.610 --> 00:40:58.940
it easy for our research knowledge base to interact with AIs

00:40:58.940 --> 00:41:04.860
so that they can give us attributable synthesized information from

00:41:04.860 --> 00:41:06.490
our lab knowledge base.

00:41:06.490 --> 00:41:09.840
So here I'm plugging in our lab graph into our favorite

00:41:09.890 --> 00:41:12.910
AI, Claude, and gave it some instructions for how

00:41:12.910 --> 00:41:16.140
it can navigate our graph and asking it to give me an

00:41:16.140 --> 00:41:19.450
update on on recent results so that we can have a real

00:41:19.450 --> 00:41:22.690
-time view of the key results in the lab and a

00:41:22.690 --> 00:41:24.700
type of real-time research assessment.

00:41:24.700 --> 00:41:27.900
So it says here are the recent results from the lab and

00:41:27.900 --> 00:41:30.500
I'll give you some links, I'll tell you who

00:41:30.500 --> 00:41:32.780
did it, I'll tell you how important it is,

00:41:32.780 --> 00:41:37.140
and we can, you know, vibe code or any arbitrary

00:41:37.140 --> 00:41:41.030
visualization or dashboard that we think might be relevant.

00:41:41.050 --> 00:41:44.680
And this, I think, reflects the the heterogeneity

00:41:44.680 --> 00:41:48.760
of algorithms that ATProto enables too, where once you

00:41:48.760 --> 00:41:53.590
and your community decide what the relevant metrics or what's the

00:41:53.590 --> 00:41:58.110
most important thing, then you can show for your community the

00:41:58.110 --> 00:42:03.320
highest relevance, in this case individual results connected to the key

00:42:03.410 --> 00:42:08.540
questions, motivated by a piece of evidence that I collected that

00:42:08.540 --> 00:42:12.380
's in my one of my postdoc papers and connected to

00:42:12.410 --> 00:42:18.060
an undergraduate's result as well that you can freely navigate through

00:42:18.090 --> 00:42:20.810
the graph and then also contribute to.

00:42:20.810 --> 00:42:26.850
We now can share our research not only in long-form

00:42:27.070 --> 00:42:32.680
narratives but also in these modular research elements which we call the

00:42:32.680 --> 00:42:34.010
evidence bundle.

00:42:34.010 --> 00:42:38.310
The evidence bundle is a data object that contains the observation,

00:42:38.350 --> 00:42:41.820
the key figure, and a little bit of methods context and

00:42:41.820 --> 00:42:45.200
optionally the the raw data and the plots that led to

00:42:45.200 --> 00:42:48.700
the creation of this plot, which get remixed and re

00:42:48.710 --> 00:42:50.900
used in different contexts.

00:42:50.940 --> 00:42:55.700
The evidence bundle was born in my lab notebook in Rome and

00:42:55.740 --> 00:42:59.830
I use our discourse graph software to inventory it and update it

00:42:59.830 --> 00:43:01.120
over time.

00:43:01.120 --> 00:43:05.900
It then becomes a persistent object in the lab's graph with

00:43:05.900 --> 00:43:08.670
enough information for the rest of the lab to understand it,

00:43:08.670 --> 00:43:13.450
which we can then connect into these mini discourse graphs that support

00:43:13.460 --> 00:43:14.940
our ongoing hypotheses.

00:43:14.940 --> 00:43:18.780
We put this in the repository somewhere and then we can use

00:43:18.780 --> 00:43:23.730
it to compile either a traditional narrative or multiple narratives in different

00:43:23.730 --> 00:43:28.060
venues for different audiences and then we can also post it on

00:43:28.060 --> 00:43:29.410
on blue sky.

00:43:29.410 --> 00:43:33.050
Right now as a prototype this evidence bundle lives in gith

00:43:33.050 --> 00:43:35.300
ub but there's no reason it couldn't live on a

00:43:35.300 --> 00:43:39.710
personal data server and then take advantage of the many apps and

00:43:39.710 --> 00:43:43.200
tools that many of you in the audience are building and I

00:43:43.210 --> 00:43:46.100
would love to do that together.

00:43:46.120 --> 00:43:51.270
So we are very excited about the promise for modular research as

00:43:51.270 --> 00:43:53.780
a way to support people's ongoing science.

00:43:53.780 --> 00:43:57.720
We think for it to take hold we need to have the

00:43:57.720 --> 00:44:04.920
attribution of your modular research contributions be more valuable useful and

00:44:05.020 --> 00:44:09.440
accurate than the current method of counting up the authorships in

00:44:09.440 --> 00:44:10.940
journal articles.

00:44:10.940 --> 00:44:17.740
So we are working on that technology and on demonstrating the ability

00:44:17.760 --> 00:44:21.460
to do modular research attribution.

00:44:21.460 --> 00:44:24.100
So here you might have two labs that are working on a

00:44:24.100 --> 00:44:25.260
similar question.

00:44:25.260 --> 00:44:27.820
We'd like to make it possible if they each have their

00:44:27.820 --> 00:44:31.960
own discourse graphs for each person to be able to submit one

00:44:31.960 --> 00:44:36.150
result and have it cited by the other lab or their larger

00:44:36.150 --> 00:44:39.900
community and one lab can request an experiment.

00:44:39.900 --> 00:44:44.330
Each result has shared upon metadata in a schema of the type

00:44:44.330 --> 00:44:48.980
that Rowan just described so that you can attribute each person

00:44:48.980 --> 00:44:54.960
's contribution in a way that initially requires some access control so

00:44:54.960 --> 00:44:59.520
that they're willing to share their work individually and then is

00:44:59.550 --> 00:45:01.380
more widely shareable.

00:45:01.380 --> 00:45:05.740
We're making this possible in a workshop catalyzing modular

00:45:05.740 --> 00:45:13.240
interoperable research attribution and in a workshop in Ireland

00:45:13.240 --> 00:45:17.710
in June where we're bringing together tool builders and researchers to

00:45:17.710 --> 00:45:22.320
make a proof of concept a system by which you can trade

00:45:22.320 --> 00:45:27.840
individual research elements and Ronan and I have co-founded

00:45:27.840 --> 00:45:32.300
a community of organizations called the Kairos Network which is

00:45:32.300 --> 00:45:37.290
meant to support different tool building organizations that have shared values that

00:45:37.290 --> 00:45:40.950
are committed to interoperability so that modular research can be

00:45:40.950 --> 00:45:46.300
carried out with the hope that it becomes a persistent and sustainable

00:45:46.300 --> 00:45:52.460
source of support for this tool this new tool building ecosystem.

00:45:53.740 --> 00:45:58.550
So in summary by decoupling research into its atomic elements

00:45:58.710 --> 00:46:03.770
questions claims and evidence and connecting them into a graph we enable

00:46:03.770 --> 00:46:09.590
trainees experts and AIs alike to make discrete contributions to shared

00:46:09.670 --> 00:46:14.280
research collaborations in a way where you can see the direct proven

00:46:14.280 --> 00:46:18.540
ance you can attribute each person's contribution and you can build

00:46:18.550 --> 00:46:23.840
upon it in a way that leaves space for each researcher to

00:46:23.840 --> 00:46:29.810
be recognized and allows them to work collaboratively with AIs

00:46:29.810 --> 00:46:34.220
and with each other and preserve the most fun parts of doing

00:46:34.220 --> 00:46:35.500
research together.

